title: AD pt1
characteristics_ch1: sort population: Live CD45+ CD13- CD3- CD56dim,disease state: atopic dermatitis,barcode: AAATGCA
extract_protocol_ch1: Cells were sorted directly into lysis buffer containing TCEP according to manufacturer's instructions, vortexed for 30 seconds, and then frozen on dry ice. Total RNA was extracted from 30-100,000 sorted NK cells using the Macherey-Nagel RNA Nucleospin XS kit.,Libraries were constructed using the CloneTech SMARTer cDNA amplification kit with 10 ng of total RNA.
data_processing: Sequences were aligned with STAR v2.0.4b,Gene counts were determined with Subread:featureCount v1.4.5,Transcript abundance was determined with Sailfish v0.6.3,Sequence performace was assessed with RSeQC v2.3,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: Processed data files are the counts tables from Subread:featureCount for each sample as a text file, as well as a compiled csv file of RPKMs for each sample

title: ad013
characteristics_ch1: tissue: skin,tissue: atopic dermatitis
extract_protocol_ch1: 4 mm skin biopsies of skin from atopic dermatitis patients or deidentified healthy margin surgical tissue were obtained; skin samples were placed in RNA Later and tissue was lysed using a bead homogenizer followed by RNA isolation using the RNeasy mini kit (QIAGEN),rRNA was depleted using RiboZERO kit (Illumina), mRNA was fragmented in buffer containing 40 mM Tris acetate (pH 8.2), 100 mM potassium acetate, and 30 mM magnesium acetate and heated to 94C for 150 s. mRNA was reverse transcribed to yield cDNA using SuperScript III RT enzyme (Invitrogen, per manufacturerâs instructions) and random hexamers. A second strand reaction was performed to yield dscDNA. cDNA was blunt ended, had an A base added to the 30 ends, and then had Illumina sequencing adapters ligated to the ends. Ligated fragments were then amplified for 12 cycles using primers incorporating unique index tags. Fragments were sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq-3000 using single reads extending 50 bases.
data_processing: Sequences were aligned with STAR v2.0.4b,Gene counts were determined with Subread:featureCount v1.4.5,Transcript abundance was determined with Sailfish v0.6.3,Sequence performace was assessed with RSeQC v2.3,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: Processed data files are the counts tables from Subread:featureCount for each sample as a text file

title: S13_S5
characteristics_ch1: ptid: 2007,timepoint: BL,treatment: Cerdulatinib,tissue: skin,disease state: Lesional,patient diagnosis: Mild-to-Moderate Atopic Dermatitis
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted from skin biopsy samples using Qiagen miRNeasy Mini kit.,The libraries were generated using TruSeq Stranded mRNA Library Prep kit following manufactory protocol. Briefly, mRNA was first extracted from 240ng of total RNA using oligo-dT magnetic beads and fragmented at high temperature. A cDNA library was then prepared from the fragemented mRNA by revervse transcription, second strand synthesis and ligation of specific adapters.,Next generation sequencing was performed on Illumina Hiseq 4000 with single-ended 100 red cycles. Image analysis and bases calling was conducted in real-time by the Illumina analysis pipeline.
data_processing: RNA-seq sample quality was assessed using FastQC and MultiQC.,Samples were aligned to human reference genome based on STAR RNA-sequencing aligner and sequencing reads were assigned to genomic features by featureCounts.,Genomic features with 0 counts in more than 20% of the samples were filtered out.,Data was then transfromed to log2-counts per million by voom-transform.,Fold changes (FCHs) vs. baseline were estimated and hypothesis testing was conducted with contrasts under the general framework for linear models in limma package. P-values were adjusted using the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure, which controls False Discovery Rate (FDR).,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: log2-counts per million
contact_institute: Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai

A cDNA library was then prepared from the fragemented mRNA by revervse transcription, second strand synthesis and ligation of specific adapters.,Next generation sequencing was performed on Illumina Hiseq 4000 with single-ended 100 red cycles. Image analysis and bases calling was conducted in real-time by the Illumina analysis pipeline.
data_processing: RNA-seq sample quality was assessed using FastQC and MultiQC.,Samples were aligned to human reference genome based on STAR RNA-sequencing aligner and sequencing reads were assigned to genomic features by featureCounts.,Genomic features with 0 counts in more than 20% of the samples were filtered out.,Data was then transfromed to log2-counts per million by voom-transform.,Fold changes (FCHs) vs. baseline were estimated and hypothesis testing was conducted with contrasts under the general framework for linear models in limma package. P-values were adjusted using the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure, which controls False Discovery Rate (FDR).,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: log2-counts per million
contact_institute: Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai

extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted from skin biopsy samples using Qiagen miRNeasy Mini kit.,The libraries were generated using TruSeq Stranded mRNA Library Prep kit following manufactory protocol. Briefly, mRNA was first extracted from 240ng of total RNA using oligo-dT magnetic beads and fragmented at high temperature. A cDNA library was then prepared from the fragemented mRNA by revervse transcription, second strand synthesis and ligation of specific adapters.,Next generation sequencing was performed on Illumina Hiseq 4000 with single-ended 100 red cycles. Image analysis and bases calling was conducted in real-time by the Illumina analysis pipeline.
data_processing: RNA-seq sample quality was assessed using FastQC and MultiQC.,Samples were aligned to human reference genome based on STAR RNA-sequencing aligner and sequencing reads were assigned to genomic features by featureCounts.,Genomic features with 0 counts in more than 20% of the samples were filtered out.,Data was then transfromed to log2-counts per million by voom-transform.,Fold changes (FCHs) vs. baseline were estimated and hypothesis testing was conducted with contrasts under the general framework for linear models in limma package. P-values were adjusted using the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure, which controls False Discovery Rate (FDR).,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: log2-counts per million
contact_institute: Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai

characteristics_ch1: patient diagnosis: Atopic Dermatitis,ptid: 264-501,timepoint: Baseline,treatment: SB414 2%,tissue: skin,tissue disease state: Non-Les
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted from skin biopsy samples using Qiagen miRNeasy Mini kit.,The libraries were generated using TruSeq Stranded mRNA Library Prep kit following manufactory protocol. Briefly, mRNA was first extracted from 240ng of total RNA using oligo-dT magnetic beads and fragmented at high temperature. A cDNA library was then prepared from the fragemented mRNA by revervse transcription, second strand synthesis and ligation of specific adapters.,Next generation sequencing was performed on Illumina Hiseq 4000 with single-ended 100 red cycles. Image analysis and bases calling was conducted in real-time by the Illumina analysis pipeline.
data_processing: RNA-seq sample quality was assessed using FastQC and MultiQC.,Samples were aligned to human reference genome based on STAR RNA-sequencing aligner and sequencing reads were assigned to genomic features by featureCounts.,Genomic features with 0 counts in more than 20% of the samples were filtered out.,Data was then transfromed to log2-counts per million by voom-transform.,Fold changes (FCHs) vs. baseline were estimated and hypothesis testing was conducted with contrasts under the general framework for linear models in limma package. P-values were adjusted using the Benjamini-Hochberg procedure, which controls False Discovery Rate (FDR).,Genome_build: GRCh38,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: log2-counts per million
contact_institute: Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai

title: Patient_1_AL_m0
characteristics_ch1: patient id: Patient_1,disease state: atopic dermatitis,timepoint: baseline (m0),tissue: skin
extract_protocol_ch1: RNAlater fixed skin tissue samples were disrupted using innuSPEED Lysis Tubes W (1.4 â 1.6 mm steel beads & 3.5 mm ceramic beads) (Analytik Jena, Jena, Germany) in a SpeedMill Plus (3x 1min intervals) (Analytik Jena) in Lysis/Binding Buffer (Lifetechnologies). Total RNA was isolated using the mirVanaTM miRNA Isolation Kit (Lifetechnologies, Carlsbad, CA) following the manufacturers specifications with an additional on-column DNase treatment.,RNA libraries were prepared for sequencing using standard Illumina protocols (TruSeq stranded mRNA)
data_processing: Illumina bcl2fastq v2.20.0.422 software used for basecalling.,Illumina standard primers were trimmed using cutadapt (version 1.15),Reads were mapped to the human reference genome (GRCh38, Ensembl release 91) using Tophat2 (version 2.1.1) and Bowtie2 (version 2.3.2),Mapped reads were cleaned and sorted using Samtools (version 1.5),Number of reads for each gene was counted using HTSeq (version 0.10.0) and annotated according to the Gencode version 27 annotation gtf file,Genome_build: GRCh38, Ensembl release 91,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: Tab-delimited text file includes raw counts as generated by HTSeq

extract_protocol_ch1: RNAlater fixed skin tissue samples were disrupted using innuSPEED Lysis Tubes W (1.4 â 1.6 mm steel beads & 3.5 mm ceramic beads) (Analytik Jena, Jena, Germany) in a SpeedMill Plus (3x 1min intervals) (Analytik Jena) in Lysis/Binding Buffer (Lifetechnologies). Total RNA was isolated using the mirVanaTM miRNA Isolation Kit (Lifetechnologies, Carlsbad, CA) following the manufacturers specifications with an additional on-column DNase treatment.,RNA libraries were prepared for sequencing using standard Illumina protocols (TruSeq stranded mRNA)
data_processing: Illumina bcl2fastq v2.20.0.422 software used for basecalling.,Illumina standard primers were trimmed using cutadapt (version 1.15),Reads were mapped to the human reference genome (GRCh38, Ensembl release 91) using Tophat2 (version 2.1.1) and Bowtie2 (version 2.3.2),Mapped reads were cleaned and sorted using Samtools (version 1.5),Number of reads for each gene was counted using HTSeq (version 0.10.0) and annotated according to the Gencode version 27 annotation gtf file,Genome_build: GRCh38, Ensembl release 91,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: Tab-delimited text file includes raw counts as generated by HTSeq

title: Dermatitis_tape_NL (11)
characteristics_ch1: individual: patient number 1,gender: M,age: 63,localization: hand,easi: 7,disease state: Atopic dermatitis,tissue: Stratum corneum,skin site: NL,sample type: tape
extract_protocol_ch1: Total RNA was extracted using the Exiqon miRCURYâ¢ RNA Isolation Kit - Cell and Plant (Exiqon, now Qiagen Denmark, Copenhagen, Denmark) following the manufacturerâs recommendation, with additional heating of the lysis buffer to 56Â°C for 5 min before adding 70% ethanol (Qiagen Denmark, Copenhagen, Denmark).,Library preparation was performed with the SMARTer Stranded Total RNA-Seq Kit v2 - Pico Input Mammalian kit (Takara Bio Europe, Saint-Germain-en-Laye, France) following the manufacturerâs recommendation without fragmentation. To capture all RNA transcripts, the kit uses random hexamer primers for amplification. The protocol included removal of ribosomal RNA. For comparability, the same protocol was used for all sample types.,Single-end sequencing (75 bp) was performed with a NextSeq 500 (Illumina Denmark, Copenhagen, Denmark)
data_processing: BCL files were converted to FASTQ files with the bcl2fastq software (Illumina, California, USA),Adapters as well as consecutive stretches of low-quality bases (Q<30) from the 5â and 3â termini were removed using AdapterRemoval version 2.1.3.  A length threshold of 20 bp was used for read removal.,Reads were aligned using STAR (Spliced Transcripts Alignment to a Reference) version 2.5.3a with default settings  where reads with multiple alignment were discarded.,Genome_build: For alignment, the Gene transfer format (GTF) annotation file for the hg38 reference genome (from the GENCODE consortium release 27) were used.,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: One processed .txt matrix containing Deseq2 normalized abundance data for all samples. One non-lesional tape sample was excluded due to low number of reads (<0.5M), and another lesional and non-lesional tape sample were excluded due to contamination of the samples.  The excluded samples are: 31, 35, 81 (not included in this GEO study).

title: Skin-atopic dermatitis lesion-01
characteristics_ch1: disease state: atopic dermatitis,tissue: skin (epidermis+dermis),age (yr-old): 20
extract_protocol_ch1: RNA extract from epidermis and skin, flash frozen on dry ice, and RNA was harvested using Trizol reagent. Illumina TruSeq RNA Sample Prep Kit was used with 1 ug of total RNA for the construction of sequencing libraries.,RNA libraries were prepared for sequencing using standard Illumina protocols
data_processing: To separate human RNA seq reads, we used bbpsplit including bbmap package(https://sourceforge.net/projects/bbmap/),Low quality reads were filtered according to the following criteria; N-ratio > 0.1 and ratio of less than Phred quality score 20 > 0.4,Filtered reads were mapped to the human reference genome (Ensembl release 72) using the aligner STAR v.2.3.0e.,Gene expression level was measured with Cufflinks v2.1.1 (Trapnell C. et al, 2010) using the gene annotation database of Ensembl release 72.,For differential expression analysis, gene level count data were generated using HTSeq-count v0.5.4p3 (Anders S. et al, 20140) tool with the option "-m intersection-nonemptyâ and -r option considering paired-end sequence.,Genome_build: mm9,Supplementary_files_format_and_content: To characterize the identified genes from DEG analysis, GO based trend test was performed using the Fisherâs exact test
contact_institute: Yonsei University Wonju College of Medicine
